nd":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret was born about 1482, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard William Adams in 1504, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1530, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 49."},"et":{"about 1482–1530":"umbes 1482–1530","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1510–1563":"1510–1563","1482–1530":"1482–1530","1478":"1478","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1482":"1482","Abt 1510":"umbes 1510","about 1482":"umbes 1482","1504":"1504","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1482–1530":"noin 1482–1530","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1510–1563":"1510–1563","1482–1530":"1482–1530","1478":"1478","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1482":"1482","Abt 1510":"noin 1510","about 1482":"noin 1482","1504":"1504","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1482–1530":"environ 1482–1530","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1510–1563":"1510–1563","1482–1530":"1482–1530","1478":"1478","1510":"1510","1530":"1530","1563":"1563","1482":"1482","Abt 1510":"environ 1510","about 1482":"environ 1482","1504":"1504","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Angleterre","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staf